  "prompt": "How do bottle caps work in Pokemon Sun / Moon?",
  "response": "Bottle Caps in Pokemon Sun and Moon are items used to **raise the IVs (Individual Values) of a Pokemon**. They are part of a feature called **Hyper Training**. Here's a breakdown of how they work:\n\n*   **Individual Values (IVs):** Every Pokemon has IVs, which are hidden numbers ranging from 0 to 31 for each of its six stats (HP, Attack, Defense, Special Attack, Special Defense, and Speed). These IVs are like genetic potential and contribute to how high a stat can ultimately reach. Higher IVs mean higher stats.\n\n*   **Hyper Training:** This is a method to maximize a Pokemon's stats by effectively setting their IVs to their maximum possible value (31) for the stats you choose.\n\n*   **How Bottle Caps are Used:**\n    *   **Location:** You can hyper train your Pokemon at **Heahea City's Shopping Mall** from **Mr. Hyper**, who is located behind the Poke Center.\n\n    *   **Requirements:**\n        *   **Level 100:**  Your Pokemon MUST be at Level 100 to be eligible for Hyper Training.\n        *   **Bottle Caps:** You need one Bottle Cap to maximize **one** of your Pokemon's IVs. A **Gold Bottle Cap** can maximize **all six** IVs at once.\n\n    *   **Process:** Talk to Mr. Hyper, select the Level 100 Pokemon you want to train, and then choose the stat you want to maximize using a Bottle Cap (or use a Gold Bottle Cap to maximize all of them).\n\n*   **Important Considerations:**\n\n    *   **Not Permanent Breeding:**  While Hyper Training raises the stats as if the IVs were perfect, it's important to understand that the **actual IVs remain the same**. This means:\n        *   **Breeding:** Hyper Training does NOT affect breeding. The Pokemon will still pass down its original IVs when breeding.\n        *   **Hidden Power:** The type of Hidden Power a Pokemon learns is determined by its IVs, so Hyper Training **will not change** the Hidden Power type.\n\n    *   **Visual Indication:** After Hyper Training, the stat screen will show the word \"Best\" next to the stats that have been maxed out with Hyper Training, indicating that they are functionally maxed even though their true IV is not 31.\n\n*   **How to Obtain Bottle Caps:**\n\n    *   **Fishing:** Sometimes found while fishing.\n    *   **Festival Plaza:** Exchange Festival Coins for Bottle Caps.\n    *   **Poke Pelago:** Can be found in Isle Abeens.\n    *   **Battle Tree:** Exchange Battle Points (BP) for Bottle Caps.\n    *   **Various Events:** Can be rewards from special in-game events.\n\nIn essence, Bottle Caps provide a way to overcome less-than-perfect IVs in Pokemon that you want to use competitively, but they don't permanently change the Pokemon's underlying genetic makeup in terms of breeding or other IV-dependent mechanics.",
